# managed-nodes.allow — operator-owned allowlist of the remote hosts THIS node manages.
#
# Install as ~/.claude/managed-nodes.allow (or point CCC_MANAGED_NODES_ALLOW at it).
# One host per line. `#` starts a comment; blank lines are ignored. fnmatch globs
# are supported (`*`, `?`, `[...]`).
#
# What it does: for a Bash command whose ONLY remote reach (via ssh / scp / rsync /
# sftp / `systemctl -H`) is to hosts listed here, guard.py treats the operation as
# your own-node management and relaxes the blast-radius gates for that statement —
# secret/key deployment (`scp deploy.env node:`), remote cleanup
# (`ssh node "rm -rf /var/log/old"`), remote service control including config verbs
# (`ssh node "systemctl daemon-reload"`), and host lifecycle (`ssh node reboot`).
#
# What it does NOT do (stays fail-closed even with a host listed):
#   - any operation to a host NOT in this list (real exfil to an attacker endpoint);
#   - curl/wget/nc/ncat/ftp egress of a credential file (use scp/rsync to deploy);
#   - review-gated classes regardless of host: force-push to a protected branch,
#     history rewrite, release/publish, DB destructive/migrate;
#   - a LOCAL destructive op chained alongside a managed remote op (fail-closed).
#
# TRUST: this file is the boundary that says "these hosts are mine." guard.py
# denies agent writes to it (Edit/Write and shell redirect/interpreter writes) —
# only YOU edit it. List a host here only if you genuinely operate it; a hostname
# that resolves (via ~/.ssh/config or DNS) to a machine you do not control would
# extend the relaxation to that machine.

# --- examples (delete these; add your real fleet) ---
nosuk
gwakga
# a glob for a subnet's internal names:
# edge-*.fleet.internal
